Support Vector Machine

support vector classifier

Criando dados com 20 observaes de duas variveis, V1 e V2 e uma varivel resposta y:

set.seed(10111)
x=matrix(rnorm(40),20,2)
y=rep(c(-1,1),c(10,10))
x[y==1,]=x[y==1,]+1
dat = data.frame(x,y=as.factor(y))
plot(x,col=y+3,pch=19)

Criando um modelo svm linear (support vector classifier) com custo 1:

library(e1071)
modelo.linear = svm(y~.,data=dat,kernel="linear",cost=2,scale=F)
summary(modelo.linear)
## 
## Call:
## svm(formula = y ~ ., data = dat, kernel = "linear", cost = 2, scale = F)
## 
## 
## Parameters:
##    SVM-Type:  C-classification 
##  SVM-Kernel:  linear 
##        cost:  2 
## 
## Number of Support Vectors:  8
## 
##  ( 4 4 )
## 
## 
## Number of Classes:  2 
## 
## Levels: 
##  -1 1

O nmero de support vectors selecionados para custo 2 foi 8. Agora aumentemos o custo para 10:

library(e1071)
modelo.linear = svm(y~.,data=dat,kernel="linear",cost=10,scale=F)
summary(modelo.linear)
## 
## Call:
## svm(formula = y ~ ., data = dat, kernel = "linear", cost = 10, scale = F)
## 
## 
## Parameters:
##    SVM-Type:  C-classification 
##  SVM-Kernel:  linear 
##        cost:  10 
## 
## Number of Support Vectors:  6
## 
##  ( 3 3 )
## 
## 
## Number of Classes:  2 
## 
## Levels: 
##  -1 1

O nmero de support vector com custo 10 diminui para 6.

Pontos selecionados como support vectors:

support_vectors = x[modelo.linear$index,]
support_vectors
##            [,1]        [,2]
## [1,]  0.4992207  0.83459057
## [2,]  0.7136758  0.09454017
## [3,] -0.2485535  0.68234694

Plot no muito bonito:

plot(modelo.linear,dat)

Construo de uma grade para valores de X1 e X2

intervalo=apply(x,2,range)
x1 = seq(from=intervalo[1,1],to=intervalo[2,1],length=75)
x2 = seq(from=intervalo[1,2],to=intervalo[2,2],length=75)
xgrid = expand.grid(X1=x1,X2=x2) # cria um espao contnuo

ygrid=predict(modelo.linear,xgrid)

plot(xgrid,col=c('red','blue')[as.numeric(ygrid)],pch=20,cex=.2)

# pontos originais
points(x,col=y+3,pch=19)

# suport vectors
points(support_vectors,pch=5,cex=2)

# Adicionado as margens (decision boundary):
beta=drop( t(modelo.linear$coefs) %*% support_vectors )
beta0=modelo.linear$rho
abline(beta0/beta[2],-beta[1]/beta[2])

# margem superior
abline((beta0-1)/beta[2],-beta[1]/beta[2],lty=2)

# margem inferior
abline((beta0+1)/beta[2],-beta[1]/beta[2],lty=2)

Cross Validation

set.seed(1)
cv_svm = tune(svm,y~.,data=dat,kernel="linear",scale=F,
              ranges=list(cost=c(0.001,0.01,0.1,1,5,10,100)))
summary(cv_svm)
##

O resultado no diz que o melhor modelo foi o de custo 100 (best performance: 0.1). Podemos acess-lo com best.model:

melhor_modelo = cv_svm$best.model

non-linear vector machine

data = read.csv('data/svm_nonlinear.csv')
data$y = as.factor(data$y)
plot(data[,2:3],col=as.numeric(data$y))

modelo_nao_linear=svm(y~.,data=data,kernel="radial",cost=5,scale=F)

Grfico mais bonito:

intervalo = apply(data[,2:3],2,range)
x1 = seq(from=intervalo[1,1],to=intervalo[2,1],length=75)
x2 = seq(from=intervalo[1,2],to=intervalo[2,2],length=75)
xgrid = expand.grid(X1=x1,X2=x2) # cria um espao contnuo
ygrid=predict(modelo_nao_linear,xgrid)

plot(xgrid,col=as.numeric(ygrid),pch=20,cex=.2)

# pontos originais
points(data[,2:3],col=as.numeric(data$y),pch=19)
